result.execSummary:
The defendant Patrick Ward Rhodes was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Patrick Ward Rhodes is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Patrick Ward Rhodes was found guilty of Stalking, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.32(2).
  • Patrick Ward Rhodes was found guilty of Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Judgement of Conviction

Case called at 3:24 PM.  State appeared by District Attorney Jenna Gill.  Defendant Patrick Ward Rhodes in court, in custody with Attorney Guy Mason Taylor.  Attorney Taylor informs court Defendant has reviewed revocation summary, recommend 9 months probation, concurrent.  State has reviewed file and agrees with 9 months.  Attorney Taylor states remarks are inflammatory.  State has no facts to support those remarks and states Defendant does have 147 days jail time credit and has 133 days left to serve.  Attorney Taylor makes statement to Court.  Defendant makes statement to the Court.  Court will support Mr. McDermott's recommendation and impose 9 months county jail time on counts 1 and 4 concurrent.  Attorney Taylor will review appellate rights with client.  Defendant is returned to custody of Lafayette County Jail to serve out remainder of sentence.

Defendant Patrick Ward Rhodes in court with attorney Nancy L. Moore.  Katherine M. Findley appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court questions defendant re: plea and waiver of rights, court also questions attorney Moore re: her clients plea and waiver of rights.
Court finds plea and waiver is made freely knowingly and intelligently.
Court accepts plea and finds the defendant "GUILTY" to Counts 1 & 4.
State moves for Joint Recommendation of the parties (Plea Agreement).
Attorney Moore concurs with the State.

Count 4- Sentence withheld Probation for a period of 2 years with conditions.
